  "text": "Early in its development SIDT predicted no effect of age on children's intergroup beliefs and attitudes [CITATION_1] ). However, data from supported the age predictions suggested by SCT. As a result, Nesdale and colleagues suggested that children traverse four stages of social identity development between the ages of 2 and 7. According to this paradigm, progression to ethnic preference (age 4 to 5), and especially to ethnic prejudice (age 6 to 7), depends on the acquisition of self-identifi cation, understanding of social structure, ability to engage in social comparison, and preference to belong to a high-status group.",
